  { step: "Register with SVS", duration: "Immediately after Gewerbeschein", location: "SVS office" },
  { step: "Apply for residence permit", duration: "2-4 months processing", location: "MA 35 (Vienna) or BH" },
  { step: "Register with Finanzamt", duration: "Within 1 month", location: "Tax office" },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Austria Freelancer Visa 2026: Requirements, SVS Insurance & Application Guide"
  description="Complete guide to Austria's Freelancer Visa (Rot-Weiß-Rot Karte, Selbständige). Mandatory SVS insurance, points system, Gewerbeschein requirements, and step-by-step application process for Vienna and beyond."
  headline="Austria Freelancer Visa: Insurance & Requirements Guide"
  subheadline="Everything you need to know about freelancing in Austria—Rot-Weiß-Rot Karte points system, mandatory SVS social insurance, trade license requirements, and life in Vienna, consistently ranked the world's most livable city."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Freelancer Insurance"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/allianz-care"
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/visas/freelancer-visa-hero-bg.png"
>

  <!-- Trust Signals -->
  <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 mb-8 text-sm text-neutral-600">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Updated February 2026
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Official Austrian Requirements
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      SVS Insurance Mandatory
    </span>
  </div>

  <!-- Section: Overview -->
  <section id="overview" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria has become an increasingly attractive destination for freelancers and self-employed professionals. Vienna consistently ranks as the world's most livable city, offering a combination of high quality of life, excellent healthcare, central European location, and a sophisticated business environment. For freelancers willing to navigate the Austrian bureaucracy, the rewards are substantial.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Unlike some European countries with simpler freelance pathways, Austria requires freelancers to integrate into its comprehensive social insurance system. This means higher costs upfront—approximately 27% of income goes to SVS (Sozialversicherung der Selbständigen)—but it also means you get full access to excellent healthcare and build pension entitlements from day one.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts: Austria Freelancer Visa</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-primary-800">
        <li>• <strong>Visa types:</strong> Rot-Weiß-Rot Karte für Selbständige (points-based) or Niederlassungsbewilligung – Selbständiger</li>
        <li>• <strong>Income requirement:</strong> ~€1,100-1,400/month minimum (sufficient means)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Health insurance:</strong> MANDATORY—SVS social insurance (~27% of income)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Trade license:</strong> Gewerbeschein required for most activities</li>
        <li>• <strong>Duration:</strong> 1-2 years initially, renewable</li>
        <li>• <strong>Path to PR:</strong> Permanent residence after 5 years</li>
        <li>• <strong>German language:</strong> A1-B1 required or strongly recommended</li>
        <li>• <strong>Key cities:</strong> Vienna, Salzburg, Graz, Innsbruck, Linz</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Non-EU vs. EU/EEA Citizens</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The path to freelancing in Austria differs significantly based on your citizenship:
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Non-EU Citizens</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Need Rot-Weiß-Rot Karte (points-based) OR</li>
          <li>• Niederlassungsbewilligung – Selbständiger</li>
          <li>• Must demonstrate economic benefit to Austria</li>
          <li>• Points system considers qualifications, language, age</li>
          <li>• Apply at Austrian embassy before arrival</li>
          <li>• Processing takes 2-4 months</li>
          <li>• Visa fee: €120-160</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">EU/EEA/Swiss Citizens</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• No visa required—freedom of establishment</li>
          <li>• Simply register residence (Meldezettel)</li>
          <li>• Apply for Gewerbeschein (trade license)</li>
          <li>• Register with SVS social insurance</li>
          <li>• Register with Finanzamt (tax office)</li>
          <li>• Process takes 2-4 weeks</li>
          <li>• Much simpler overall</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Vienna advantage:</strong> Vienna has the largest freelance and startup ecosystem in Austria, with excellent coworking spaces, networking opportunities, and a growing international community. The city's MA 35 immigration office handles the most applications and is generally efficient, though appointments can have long waits.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Quick Decision Guide -->
  <section id="quick-decision" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Quick Decision Guide</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Austria is Right For You If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ You value quality of life and safety</li>
          <li>✓ You want comprehensive social insurance coverage</li>
          <li>✓ You can handle ~27% SVS contributions</li>
          <li>✓ You speak or are willing to learn German</li>
          <li>✓ You want a central European base</li>
          <li>✓ You appreciate culture, history, and outdoor activities</li>
          <li>✓ You're prepared for detailed bureaucracy</li>
          <li>✓ You have qualifications that score points (RWR Card)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Consider Other Options If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• You want lower social insurance costs (try Portugal)</li>
          <li>• You prefer warmer climate (Spain, Portugal, Italy)</li>
          <li>• You don't want to learn German (Netherlands)</li>
          <li>• You're just starting out with minimal qualifications</li>
          <li>• You want minimal bureaucracy (Estonia e-Residency)</li>
          <li>• You can't afford initial 27% SVS contributions</li>
          <li>• You need a points-based system but can't reach 50 points</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>The Austrian trade-off:</strong> Austria's mandatory SVS contributions (~27% of income) are higher than many countries, but they include health insurance, pension, and accident insurance. If you're planning to stay long-term, you'll appreciate building pension entitlements. If you're looking for the cheapest option, Austria isn't it—but the quality of life and coverage are exceptional.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Visa Requirements -->
  <section id="requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Visa Requirements</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Non-EU freelancers have two main pathways: the Rot-Weiß-Rot Karte für Selbständige (points-based) or the Niederlassungsbewilligung – Selbständiger (settlement permit for self-employed). The RWR Card is generally preferred as it offers a clearer pathway and longer initial validity.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={requirementsColumns} rows={requirementsRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Rot-Weiß-Rot Card Points System</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      To qualify for the RWR Card for Self-Employed, you need at least 50 points. Points are awarded based on qualifications, professional experience, language skills, and age. Here's how the system works:
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={pointsColumns} rows={pointsRows} />

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6 mb-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>Important:</strong> Beyond meeting the 50-point threshold, you must also demonstrate that your business will provide economic benefit to Austria. This typically means showing how your services will serve Austrian clients, create employment, or bring investment/innovation to the country. A strong business plan is essential.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Essential Documents</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Required for All Applicants</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Valid passport (6+ months validity)</li>
          <li>• Completed application form (Antrag)</li>
          <li>• Biometric passport photos</li>
          <li>• Proof of accommodation in Austria</li>
          <li>• Criminal record certificate (apostilled)</li>
          <li>• Health insurance confirmation</li>
          <li>• Proof of sufficient financial means</li>
          <li>• Business plan demonstrating economic benefit</li>
          <li>• Birth certificate (apostilled)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Points Evidence (RWR Card)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Diplomas and certificates (translated, apostilled)</li>
          <li>• German/English language certificates</li>
          <li>• CV with detailed work experience</li>
          <li>• Reference letters from employers/clients</li>
          <li>• Portfolio of work</li>
          <li>• Evidence of Austrian connections (if any)</li>
          <li>• Proof of professional qualifications</li>
          <li>• Letters of intent from Austrian clients</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Financial Requirements</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria requires proof of "sufficient means" to support yourself. While there's no strict minimum income specified, immigration authorities generally look for:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Single person:</strong> ~€1,100-1,400/month (€13,200-16,800/year)</li>
      <li><strong>Couple:</strong> ~€1,700-2,100/month</li>
      <li><strong>Family with children:</strong> Additional ~€200-300 per child</li>
      <li><strong>Savings buffer:</strong> €8,000-15,000 in bank statements</li>
      <li><strong>Rental contract or housing proof</strong></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>Tip:</strong> If you have existing clients or contracts, include letters of intent or contracts in your application. Demonstrable income streams significantly strengthen your case and help prove economic benefit to Austria.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Insurance Requirements -->
  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">SVS Membership is Mandatory</h3>
      <p class="text-green-800">
        All self-employed persons in Austria must join the SVS (Sozialversicherung der Selbständigen). This is not optional. SVS contributions cover health insurance (via ÖGK), pension insurance, and accident insurance. The combined rate is approximately 27% of your income, with caps on higher earners.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria's social insurance system for the self-employed is comprehensive but expensive. Unlike Germany where you can choose between public and private insurance, Austria mandates SVS membership for all freelancers and business owners. Private insurance can only supplement SVS coverage—it cannot replace it.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">SVS vs. Private Insurance</h3>

    <ComparisonTable columns={insuranceColumns} rows={insuranceRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Understanding SVS Contributions</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      SVS contributions are calculated as a percentage of your business income:
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">SVS Contribution Breakdown (2026)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• <strong>Health insurance:</strong> ~6.8% of income</li>
          <li>• <strong>Pension insurance:</strong> ~18.5% of income</li>
          <li>• <strong>Accident insurance:</strong> ~1.9% of income</li>
          <li>• <strong>Total:</strong> ~27.2% of income</li>
          <li>• <strong>Minimum contribution (Year 1):</strong> ~€150-200/month</li>
          <li>• <strong>Maximum contribution cap:</strong> Based on max assessment base</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">What SVS Gets You</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ Full ÖGK healthcare access</li>
          <li>✓ Pension contributions for retirement</li>
          <li>✓ Accident insurance coverage</li>
          <li>✓ Sickness benefit after 3 days</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity benefits</li>
          <li>✓ e-card for cashless healthcare</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>First-year advantage:</strong> In your first year of self-employment, SVS uses a reduced minimum assessment base. This means your contributions are lower while you're getting established. However, there may be back-payments in subsequent years when your actual income is assessed.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Initial Insurance Before SVS Registration</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      You'll need health insurance to apply for your visa and residence permit. Since SVS registration happens after you arrive and register your trade, you have two options for initial coverage:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Private international insurance:</strong> Allianz Care or Cigna Global provide coverage that meets visa requirements while you're getting established</li>
      <li><strong>Austrian private insurance:</strong> UNIQA or Wiener Städtische can provide initial coverage</li>
      <li><strong>EU citizens with EHIC:</strong> Can use EHIC initially, then register with SVS</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Transition period:</strong> Once you register your Gewerbeschein and join SVS, your SVS coverage begins. Private insurance can then be cancelled or converted to supplementary coverage (Zusatzversicherung) for extras like private hospital rooms or faster specialist access.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA Box -->
  <CTABox
    variant="highlight"
    title="Need insurance for your Austrian freelancer visa application?"
    description="Compare private coverage options for the initial period before SVS registration, or supplementary plans to enhance your Austrian healthcare."
    buttonText="Compare Freelancer Insurance"
    buttonHref="/go/allianz-care"
  />

  <!-- Section: Recommended Providers -->
  <section id="recommended-providers" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For Austrian freelancers, SVS is mandatory—but you'll need private coverage for your visa application period, and you may want supplementary insurance for extras. Here are the providers most commonly used by expat freelancers in Austria.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Provider Recommendations by Situation</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying for Visa, Need Initial Coverage</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Use Allianz Care or Cigna Global for comprehensive private coverage during your application and initial arrival period. Once your Gewerbeschein is registered and SVS kicks in, you can cancel the private policy or keep it as supplementary coverage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Established Freelancer, Want Faster Access</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Consider supplementary private insurance (Zusatzversicherung) from UNIQA or Wiener Städtische. This gives you private hospital rooms, choice of chief physician, and often faster specialist appointments—while SVS handles the basics.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">EU Citizen, Quick Setup</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you're an EU citizen, you can use your EHIC for initial coverage while registering your business. Once your Gewerbeschein is active, register with SVS immediately. The process is straightforward and you'll have full coverage within weeks.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-amber-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Frequent International Traveler</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">SVS provides EU coverage via EHIC, but limited outside Europe. If you travel globally for business, keep supplementary international coverage from Allianz Care or Cigna Global for non-EU travel medical protection.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Budget-Conscious, Just Starting</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Focus on meeting the minimum requirements: private coverage for your visa application, then transition to SVS-only once registered. SVS provides comprehensive coverage. Add private supplementary insurance only if your income grows and you want extras.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

