  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating SVS Contributions</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">At ~27% of income, SVS contributions are significant. Many freelancers are shocked when they realize they're paying €400-800/month in social insurance. Budget for this from the start—it's mandatory, not optional. The upside is comprehensive coverage and pension building.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the 3-Day Meldezettel Deadline</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Austria strictly enforces the 3-day residence registration requirement. Without your Meldezettel, you cannot open bank accounts, get a trade license, or register for SVS. Go to the Meldeamt within 3 days of moving in—bring passport and rental contract.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying Without Demonstrating Economic Benefit</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Simply meeting the 50-point threshold isn't enough. You must also show how your business benefits Austria. Weak applications say "I'll work remotely for foreign clients." Strong applications include Austrian client letters of intent, partnerships with local businesses, or plans to employ others.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring German Language Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While German isn't always mandatory, it significantly helps your application (points!) and daily life. Bureaucracy is conducted in German. Contracts are in German. Learning at least A2-B1 before arrival makes everything easier and strengthens your visa application.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Hiring a Steuerberater (Tax Advisor)</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Austrian tax law is complex, with VAT decisions, income tax advance payments, and deduction optimization. The €100-300/month cost of a Steuerberater often pays for itself. They'll ensure compliance and maximize legitimate deductions. Do not try to DIY Austrian taxes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Austria -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Austria</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria has one of Europe's best healthcare systems, consistently ranking in the top 10 globally. As a freelancer with SVS membership, you get full access to the public healthcare system through ÖGK (Österreichische Gesundheitskasse)—the same quality care available to Austrian citizens.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's Covered</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Fully Covered (SVS/ÖGK)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ GP and specialist consultations</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital treatment and surgeries</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications (small copay)</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health services</li>
          <li>✓ Preventive care and screenings</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity care</li>
          <li>✓ Physical therapy and rehabilitation</li>
          <li>✓ Basic dental care</li>
          <li>✓ EU/EEA coverage via EHIC</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Additional with Private Supplementary</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Private hospital rooms (Sonderklasse)</li>
          <li>• Chief physician treatment</li>
          <li>• Better dental coverage</li>
          <li>• Alternative medicine</li>
          <li>• Faster specialist appointments</li>
          <li>• Global travel coverage</li>
          <li>• No referral needed for specialists</li>
          <li>• Hospital choice freedom</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Access Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Your e-card</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After registering with SVS, you'll receive an e-card (electronic health card). Present this at any doctor or hospital for cashless treatment. The system is efficient and widely used throughout Austria.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Finding Doctors</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Use the ÖGK website or Doctolib to find doctors who accept the e-card. Many doctors in Vienna speak English. You can see any "Kassenarzt" (contracted doctor) without referral. Private doctors charge more but may have shorter waits.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Appointments and Wait Times</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">GP appointments are usually available within days. Specialists can have 2-6 week waits with ÖGK. Private supplementary insurance often provides faster access. For urgent issues, call the 24-hour health hotline 1450.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 144 for emergencies (ambulance). Hospital emergency rooms (Notaufnahme) are available 24/7 at all major hospitals. For urgent but non-emergency issues, use the 1450 health hotline for advice.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Vienna hospitals:</strong> Vienna has excellent hospitals including AKH (Allgemeines Krankenhaus—one of Europe's largest), Wilhelminenspital, and various specialized centers. Quality is high across the public system. Private hospitals (Privatspitäler) offer luxury amenities but require supplementary insurance.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How much do SVS contributions cost?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          SVS contributions total approximately 27% of your income (health ~6.8%, pension ~18.5%, accident ~1.9%). There's a minimum contribution of roughly €150-200/month in your first year, increasing as your actual income is assessed. Higher earners hit a contribution cap. SVS contributions are fully tax-deductible.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I opt out of SVS and use only private insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. SVS membership is mandatory for all self-employed persons in Austria. You cannot opt out. Private insurance can only supplement SVS coverage—it cannot replace it. This is different from Germany where you can choose private-only. Budget for SVS from the start.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak German for the freelancer visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          For the RWR Card, German earns you points (A1=5pts, A2=10pts, B1=15pts) but isn't strictly required if you meet 50 points otherwise. However, most bureaucracy is in German, and daily life is much easier with the language. Some settlement permits require A1 German. We strongly recommend learning at least A2 before arrival.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the Gewerbeschein and do I need one?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Gewerbeschein is a trade license required to conduct business in Austria. Most freelance activities require one. Some trades are "free" (freie Gewerbe—like IT services, consulting) and easy to obtain. Others are "regulated" (reglementierte Gewerbe) and require proof of qualifications. Apply at the Bezirkshauptmannschaft or Magistrat after registering your residence.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 5 years of legal residence in Austria (including on a freelancer permit), you can apply for permanent residence (Daueraufenthalt-EU). Requirements include: 5 years continuous residence, sufficient income, health insurance, adequate accommodation, German B1, and integration exam. Permanent residence provides unlimited work rights and stays valid indefinitely.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work as an employee while having a freelancer permit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The freelancer permit (Selbständige) is specifically for self-employment. If you want to take employed work, you may need a different permit or to adjust your status. Some freelancers operate a "mixed" income (self-employed plus mini-job), but this affects your SVS category and taxes. Consult a Steuerberater before taking employed work.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria's freelancer visa offers a pathway to one of Europe's highest quality of life destinations. Vienna consistently ranks as the world's most livable city, and the combination of excellent healthcare, central location, cultural richness, and safety is hard to match. For freelancers willing to invest in the process, the rewards are substantial.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The main challenges are the mandatory SVS contributions (~27% of income) and the detailed bureaucracy. These are significant costs that catch many freelancers off guard. Unlike Germany where you can choose private insurance, Austria mandates social insurance participation. Budget accordingly—your effective tax rate plus SVS can reach 50%+ at higher incomes.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For the right person—someone with solid qualifications (to meet the 50-point threshold), willingness to learn German, and income to support the social insurance burden—Austria provides an exceptional base for European freelance life. The path to permanent residence is clear, and the quality of healthcare, infrastructure, and daily life is among Europe's best.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Austria's freelancer visa is best suited for established professionals who value quality of life over minimal costs. SVS contributions are mandatory and significant (~27% of income)—factor this into your pricing. The bureaucracy is detailed, German language helps significantly, and you need 50+ points for the RWR Card. In return, you get access to exceptional healthcare, safety, and a world-class city. For those who can meet the requirements, Austria is an outstanding long-term choice.
      </p>
